            <p rend="align(center)">THE 'OMER</p>
            <p>Is not his a beautiful day? Look out! the sun is shining clear<lb/>ly with the mild
                rays of spring, and sends not down the scorch-<lb/>ing beams which compel us in the
                summer to seek a shelter again<lb/> his oppressive heat. Everything invites us to go
                abroad and<lb/> enjoy the balmy spring.</p>
            <p>Yet do we not wander abroad in the field to enjoy awakened<lb/> nature and why? we
                felt ourselves called upon to enter our<lb/> house of worship in accordance with the
                custom of our fathers,<lb/> to celebrate this <sic>econd</sic> day of the festival
                of our redep frm<lb/>
                <placeName>Egypt</placeName>. ———</p>
            <p>We may assume the <date>Passover</date> to be the period of our early man-<lb/>hood,
                when the age of childhood and youth are already past.<lb/> —So was out education as
                a people in <placeName>Egypt</placeName>. We went there in<lb/> the boyhood of our
                nationality, and in the iron furnace of<lb/>
                <del>ntion</del> we were taught to look up to our eternal Saviour<lb/> for
                enlargement as all the gods of men's invention are helpless<lb/> themselves, without
                power to understand the Almighty's fiat.</p>
            <p>As it is with nations so is it with individuals;<lb/> The Psalmist says out days on
                earth are seventy years, and<lb/> rarely reach eighty, ; experience proves the
                correctness<lb/> of this ancient statement —— we lose the elasticity<lb/> of our
                steps, the vigor of our limbs, the light of our eyes<lb/> is dimmed, nay our
                intellect, perhaps, becomes uncertain and<lb/> vague, and those on whose advice
                nations <sic>depnded</sic>, those who<lb/> moved pub <sic>assmbls</sic> by their
                fervent <sic>eloq</sic>, the poets who<lb/> charmed multitudes by the sweetness of
                their <sic>nukbers</sic>,<lb/> musicians whose tuneful strains have become the
                delight of<lb/> the world <sic>arenow</sic> mere <sic>shdws</sic> of <sic>thr</sic>
                <sic>forn</sic> selves- —the<lb/> picture is sad &amp; depressing, it is what awaits
                us all; we<lb/> cannot avoid the pangs of <sic>dises</sic> or the terrors of
                dissolution,<lb/> they tower up before us in the dim but certain distance, and<lb/>
                neither craven fear nor daring indifference can ward off what</p>
            <p rend="Footnote.">The proof down to this <sic>wrd</sic> was sent to <persName>Mr.
                    Leeser</persName> on <date>Dec28,<lb/> 1867</date>, but he never
                    <sic>recoverd</sic>
                <sic>suffcient</sic> strength to complete<lb/> the writing of the sermon. A few days
                after the receipt of<lb/> the proof he wrote on it the following, which he intended
                for<lb/> the printer. It was found among his papers after his death:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">“I tried yesterday to write, and succeeded in jotting</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">down about twenty lines; but I find I must wait a
                <sic>littk</sic></p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">longer. There shall be no useless delay. I feel</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">easier, but suffer greatly.”</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">L.</persName>
            </p>
            <p>The twenty lines have not been found.</p>
            <p>Deliv Beth El <date>secnd Pass</date>
                <date>5618</date> or <date>5619</date>.</p>
